text: We stumbled upon this place on or way back to the car and to not take forever to decide where to eat we just decided here. When they were sitting us I checked the ratings and i don't know why it has 3 stars. Got a little scared but we tried the hibachi, and it was good. My favorite was the shrimp. Really good flavor. Least favorite was the chicken. I also didn't like that they didn't have noddles. But the service was nice and our cook was too. We tried the sushi sampler: it wasn't the great. The place could look neater and cleaner feel.

Prices made it worthwhile.

text: The food was your average hibachi grill experience ...the sauces were not that good as they were all similar with a taste of vinegar.  I would prefer a sweet, salty, and vinegar for a variety.  The best part was we got there before 6:00 for the early bird prices.  Chicken and shrimp was about 18.95 where steak and shrimp was 20.95... It was more after 6:00.  The sushi we got to go but the sushi bar was full with many choices.  My husband wanted Bud Light but the had a few types unknown to us so he declined.  Our chef cooked and left where the guy next to us put on a show.

text: We called for a reservation for 10 people.  Arrived on time and were seated promptly.  Cold beer and good service overall.  Server was a bit inexperienced but he made do the best he could.  He kept us entertained and moved on past minor errors... Sushi was very good and meals were very filling.  It was difficult to serve the 10 of us, but they did very well.  Prices were reasonable.  The restaurant could use a deep clean... many of the other restaurants in the area appeared to have higher cleanliness standards.  It was fine for what it was.

text:
I've been eating at Something's Fishy for a couple of years now and although I'm not a "Sushi Expert" I know that when you factor in cost, quality and quantity, Something's Fishy is the best sushi in Santa Barbara.

Yesterday my friend and I decided to take advantage of their "1/2 price rolls" deal and boy was it good! I had The Philadelphia, The Santa Barbara, Tempura Shrimp and California Rolls and my friends and I also ordered the "Crispy Rolls" which weren't on the menu, to split.

Quick Tip: Crispy Rolls. Enough said.

The service at the sushi bar was great and we had a lot of fun talking and taking our time. The food was more than filling and tasted so fresh. One really learns how bod sushi buffets are when you have fresh sushi for the first time in a long while.

The waitress was always on top of things refilling our drinks and splitting the checks for all 5 of us. Another great aspect about this place is it's location. With the reasonably priced (for Santa Barbara) parking lot right behind it we were able to leave our cars and just walk up and down State St. to work the food off.

I would highly recommend Something's Fishy and just one more time let me say: Crispy Rolls. Period.

text: Well, let me begin with saying this has been my boyfriend and mines go to dinner spot for over 2 years. We do like the food, he loves the hibachi steak and shrimp and I love the half-price sushi. They also have great fried rice. The food is not what I have to complain about. Though it is not the best sushi, it is great for the price. Sadly, this place has just been going down hill. We frequent it often, but I am ready to stop giving them my business. For the price of hibachi, we want better service. There is something going on since it seems every time we go there are completely new waiters. Maybe bad management, I'm not sure. But the service here is plain out starting to suck.

text:
Sally Spork reviews Something's Fishy Japanese Steakhouse & Sushi Bar

Atmosphere: Well this spot has been in SB forevaa. Very large restaurant large square tables with a man throwing knifes in the air and slicing and dicing over a skiddle so hot it spontaneously bursts into flame (how anyone walks away with their eyebrows is a wonder!) We ate at the sushi bar, packed on a Tuesday night like birds on a wire. 

Service: We were quickly seated, and asked to be at the bar. We were not greeted by the men behind the sushi bar, even when we tried to make a simple chit-chat over the sushi (I praised the presentation), there was no return. While the chefs don't have to entertain, I do enjoy when they are present and attentive, which is not the case at this establishment. These guys are dishing out volume of sushi, so this is to be expected.  

Food/drink: The sushi was good. We ate an assortment of rolls that are discounted at a happy hour of sorts. Yellow tail, eel, crab.. it was all tasty. We had a seaweed salad which was mushy as if it had been  soaking in the dressing too long.  

Summary: Something's Fishy is the Disneyland of sushi. And some locals and tourists alike will find this place entertaining. Would I go back? Probably not. I prefer the smaller, 'hole in the wall' types of sushi places and there are several to choose from in SB.

text:
I am a native Santa Barbarian and I've been going to this place for 10+ years.  Rarely have I ever had a bad experience and I always recommend Something's Fishy to folks from out of town who want a fun experience.  Not only is their sushi the best price in town (half off, all the time) but their hibachi is to die for!  Always, always, always get the fried rice!  My family is completely spoiled because their fried rice is so good.  It doesn't taste as good anywhere else.  Nearly every single hibachi chef I have had does a great job with entertaining, although every now and then (typically during the lunch hour) I have had a chef who is new/learning, so he didn't do as many tricks.  Every now and then a chef will come up with something completely different that I've never seen before, and that's always a treat!

I have had their halibut, chicken, shrimp, and steak and all of it is good.  You can't go wrong.  The best deal you can get is their deluxe filet mignon dinner which comes with miso soup, salad with an amazing ginger dressing, fried rice, grilled vegetables, and mochi ice cream for dessert.  The filet mignon simply melts in your mouth.  Exquisite.

Save room for dessert because their fried green tea ice cream is without a doubt one of my favorite desserts of all time.  You get the fried tempura outside that is warm and crunchy with the refreshing green tea ice cream center... my mouth is watering just thinking about it.

This place is definitely worth your time, but it does get busy during dinner, especially on the weekends.  So if you have a large group, I would highly recommend calling and making a reservation.  They also have an early bird special with discounts off their hibachi, as long as you get there and order between the hours of 3:00-6:00 PM.

text: We were in Santa Barbara yesterday for an event at the Fess Parker. We decided to get something to eat before driving back and we stumbled upon this Hibachi Steakhouse. We looked at the other reviews and decided to give it a try and we are delighted that we did. We were immediately greeted the moment we walked in and seated right away. We got our menus and drinks within a couple of minutes fantastic food and service, which was quite surprising based on the previous reviews of wait times and horrible service. This will be a regular spot for us. Really was impressed with one of the managers, Yukari for being on top of everything.

text:
Following the whole Hibachi/Benihana idea, Something's Fishy is a place I've been to many a time when coming home to SB. Its somehow got a little homey attachment to it for me, but after eating here quite a few times you realize that without the whole SHOW and food Dance, the food is "Meh, ok" at best. 

Getting any hibachi dish will taste essentially the same, because they use about 2 spices for everything, while fancifully grilling it on a Hibachi stove. This place isn't somewhere to go for good food. 
Instead go for the action of the chefs, the volcano onions, and all other Kitschy disneyfied food creation.
Add in some Sake Bombing, and it makes the whole experience much more fun! If you've got kids, take them here they'll love the show that puts your food, literally, on fire! My friend recalled that in his childhood he thought these kinds of chefs were "the best in the world," go here and maybe your child will think so too.

If you haven't got kids, then knock back a few sake bombs and let the fresh food with a fire-y pizazz put you in a daze, while you munch on the fire's creations. 

Note: this place's prices have gone up quite steeply over the years, and probably will go up again. As of now, its pushing the limits of value for quality/food/entertainment, but I wouldn't go if it gets any more expensive.

text:
Had it for dinner with a group of friends. Food is overpriced definitely for the Benihana-styled cooked food. It's entertaining to watch the chefs cook your food in front of you, but my steak was overcooked and really dry. The rest of the food was not that great. Service was also slow. 

The only reason we gave two stars is for the half priced sushi days, but even then it's only mediocre. The service for that was prompt, but the fish in the rolls are puny. It's filling for something cheap.

The waiting staff is helpful, but they are sometimes difficult to get ahold of. Get drink refills when you can.

text:
First time in Santa Barbara during Fiesta and apart from the festival and the confetti-filled eggs, dining at Hibachi was the highlight of my trip.

The food was amazing! The staff was great! Our chef Francisco was the star of the show! Oh and did I mention that the food was amazing?!

I highly recommend this place, whether it's for the sake bombs, hibachi, sushi, or sake bombs (yes, I know I have "sake bombs" twice but that's because of the amount of sake bombs I had that night) I'm sure you won't be disappointed.

text:
I have only come here for the sushi and for half-off sushi this is a great spot. It loses stars for its inconsistent sushi rolls. I usually like the Tomsan roll which is a yummy eel roll with other ingredients but occasionally there is hardly a piece of eel in it. However, it's half off - so I really cannot complain. The service is outstanding and the sushi chefs are great people. 

I would recommend this spot more for lunch considering dinnertime brings forth the louder and more annoying crowd. It is also filled with birthdays and this restaurant's birthday song is horrid to the ears - the tambourine needs to be destroyed! 

If you want fast, cheap sushi then this is the place for you - you will find me here often during the day!

text:
note: This review is based almost entirely on the lunch special which is usually the only times I go here.

Half priced sushi for lunch? Spending just over $10 per person and getting full on purely sushi? Hells yes. Ignore the sushi-snobs, they'll drop a star or two just because the wrap wasn't perfectly tucked-in or the rice was slightly not the way they like it. It's not the best sushi in the world, or even Santa Barbara, but it's pretty tasty and for lunch prices a steal.

Only had dinner here once with a group. Was drunk so can't comment on the food accurately but I liked it and had a pretty good time. A bit pricier in the evenings though, especially with the benihana-live grill-thing.

text:
Worst restaurant in Santa Barbara. - local review 


Last time we came here was a NIGHTMARE
- told to wait 30 mins for table
-50 mins later and multiple times checking in to see if we can get seated (empty tables everywhere)
We were seated by the manager
- told we had to wait for the other party of 2 to show up... another 20 mins...
1 hour 40 mins later... we order...
- we get our water 10 mins later and salad 20 mins later 2hours and 10 mins later....we get our food order taken....the CHEF DOES NOT SHOW UP FOR 50 minutes ------- at this point the other party literally leaves- the manager runs after them( as we catch a waiter to ask where our chef is?!?!)

They bring us deep fried crap as a sorry and fresh nice fish to the people who ran out......are you freaking kidding me? (Also we don't eat fried food)

The couple was much older... so wE believe they also judged us by age..

Our chef arrives and does not verify our orders, doesn't say hello or smile.... he seemed exhausted... 

My salmon hibachi was raw and gummy and gross!!!

Steak was good

The kicker!! They attempted to over charge us- when we had already paid!! Said we had to pay more!! I almost wanted to throw their fried tempura at them. TERRIBLE EXPERIENCE. 

Also we had at least 5 different people come to refill our waters EVERY 2 minutes!!! What is going on in this place?? Management is TERRIBLE!!!

(Brought our local friends here since they had changed from something's fishy- they were so traumatized- said will never be back!) 

The older couple sitting at our table were in a date (we were on a double date with our friends) I felt so bad for them as this older couple was clearly tourists! Shame on you - embarrassment of a business.

text: OK, If you're in SB and you want to have sushi with a big group around a chef grill and do Saki bombs (where you put a shot of hot saki on chop sticks over a glass of Soporo and yell bonzi and you pound the table making the saki drop into the beer and then chug) this is the place to go. text: At the front of restaurant, they placed a huge sign: "post a photo on Yelp and you'll get $5 off", but when you get the checks and ask for the $5 off, a photo is not sufficient.  They want to read my review.   No Thanks.  I will NOT write a good review to get $5 off.  I'm sorry , your restaurant's sushi  doesn't deserve a good review. The customer service was good, but the sushi  and rolls was tasteless.  Fish was not fresh.  It has no taste.  The rolls are mostly rice.  To make matters worst, they were skimpy on the fillings and the sauce.  Their most expensive roll ($18), which I was looking forward to try, was so bland, all I tasted was soy sauce.  I literally felt I ate a $18 bowl of white rice with soy sauce!!!  The only tasty item was their Eel sushi which was, unfortunately, ruined by long pieces of fine bones.  I'm no expert in sushi, but I have tasted better sushi in supermarket and small establishments.  Don't call yourself a sushi bar until you perfected your food.  Cost was not a factor, cuz I was expecting to pay more at tourist spots.  However, one of the worst thing you can do to a customer is charging more for inferior products.

text:
Milktooth is the place to go if you want a good breakfast cocktail and a twist on traditional brunch. At first glance of the menu, you may think you've never heard of any of these foods for breakfast, and you may be right. I guarantee no matter what you order, you're going to enjoy it. 

Milktooth is one of the most popular brunch places in Indy, which means you will typically have a wait. Trust me, it's worth the usual 30 minute wait (on weekends). To make it go by a little faster, they've got a walk up bar for their coffee drinks and pastries. Snack on one of those to give you a preview of the amazing meal you're about to have.

Their menu changes from time to time but they have a few things that stay one the menu but change ingredients. I love all of their variations on a Dutch pancake, and their raclette grilled cheese is to die for.  If you're making this a boozy breakfast, don't pass up on the michelada. And sit outside if it's warm enough!

text: Went for brunch and arrived around 11am. It was crowded already but we were seated at the counter immediately. We started with the Bottomless Drip coffee and Apple Fritter donuts. Loved the donuts and the coffee's flavor was solid, but it could have been hotter. Although, on the plus side, I didn't have to wait for it to cool down before I could drink it. Our desert was followed by the cheesy blue corn grits with all the extras (I.e. a soft poached egg, scallions and bacon bits). I'm late to the grits game but I loved them. My lovely wife had the bialy (think bagel) and lox, and miso soup. She is more of a foodie than me and a chef to boot. She was quite pleased. Service was average to good. It was cool sitting at the  counter. We got to watch the chefs in action. There was a taller female that was very focused and professional, more than most. When she wasn't cooking she was prepping and/or cleaning. Not sure why this wasn't a five star rating, probably the average service. In the end we had a great dining experience. It was pricey but you pay for what you get.

text:
This place is bananas. I've never had anything bad and most of the time my mind is blown by the innovation and deliciousness of the food. Occasionally I am disappointed by the size of a dish but generally not. 

Service is top notch although not terribly fast. Expect to wait awhile for a coffee drink other than brewed coffee but it will be worth the wait. 

Love the building. Love that the menu changes regularly although sometimes I miss an old favorite. 

Wait for seating can be longish so don't go if you're in a huge hurry. They do have a counter and a community table, which speed things up a bit if you don't mind that.

text:
I went to Milktooth over the weekend and I really wanted to love it but it was just okay.  I read through a few of the reviews before going and wasn't surprised that they were out of the fried chicken when I got there.  I wasn't planning on ordering it anyway but someone in my group tried to.  

I ended up going with the lamb patty melt and while it was good...it wasn't great.  I love having an egg on my sandwich so that was a highlight.  The lamb wasn't that great and it tasted like they combined the lamb meat with some sort of sausage but it don't state so on the menu.   The french fries were good but nothing special.  The lamb stew was the other item I was considering getting so maybe it would be worth going back and trying that.  

If you're a vegetarian you probably want to avoid this place all together because it's not very veggie friendly.  And don't think you can go and order something (like the waffle) without the bacon because your requests for revisions will be "politely declined" as it states on the menu.   I like that they tell you ahead of time but it doesn't seem like it would be a terrible thing to request that the cook doesn't sprinkle the bacon on top of the waffle. 

They do have some very interesting drinks and I would consider going there to grab a coffee because the process for coffee seemed to be quite intricate.  

I will say that the their menu has changed since they opened and a lot of what was mentioned in previous reviews is no longer on the menu.

text:
I ordered the shaved zucchini salad- it had a blue cheese yogurt, candied beets, pistachios (I think?) and some greens. Kind of small for $12, but it was good!

Also had the beausoleil oyster with chopped cucumber and some kind of mignette- delightful and you can buy them individually so you don't have to get a full order like many places!

The rose sour cocktail was right up my alley- slightly sweet and made with bubbles- how could I not like it?

We also ordered the sorghum bacon- thick cut like pork belly- sweet sauce! Yummy! 

I really LOVE LOVE LOVE the decor and atmosphere here, eclectic industrial and slightly vintage- so super cute!  

The menu changes quite frequently so be sure to check back often!

text:
Get the bacon. Get the coffee. Get the pancakes. Get everything. 
(Get your wallet ready too cuz it's not cheap).
Milktooth fulfills all your hipster brunch dreams - from the tatted chefs to the cool-clothed waiters to the converetrd garage dining area. It seems like a pretty exclusive team. However, once you order and wait (for a bit despite the slow Tuesday afternoon), the taste is so worth it. My table got the berry pancakes, the savory pancakes, and the grilled cheese with truffles. I also got the bacon, which came out in thick fat slices. Its probably the best bacon I ever had. 
The mango smoothie rivaled a mango lassi, and everything was really delicious. 
uffle oil with aged cheddar grilled cheese. The grill cheese had the perfect savory combo of sweet n salty topped with an egg cooked just right. You can't get more flavorful than this 
I definitely think this is one of those restaurants that everyone should visit!

text:
The breakfast menu and pastry menu changes so some visits I have liked more than others, but I love the way they do there menu, the overall quality is top notch. The food is funky and creative. I would not say its an every weekend brunch spot with the old reliable eggs florentine​/pancakes but it is fun and I love coming here from time to time. Beware the line can get long but they have very good coffee and pastries​ to hold you over while you wait.

p.s. The restaurant​ vibes are great!

text: Excellent food, terrible service. The food is always fabulous, so much so that it would receive a 4-star if the service were good. Each time we have been in it takes 10 minutes to get water and your drink order placed. Then the food for the whole table never comes out together, normally one person is waiting on his/her dish. The ambience and decor is fabulous and I hope with time the service gets on par with the food.

text:
During that Final Four weekend, I was trying to go to Yolk but failed to find a parking spot. I stopped and did some Yelping and found Milktooth at Fountain Square. 

When I arrive, I ended up with 30 minutes waiting. I was pleased because this usually means good food. I love waiting for seats. 

I ended up sitting at the bar to see the awesome chef cooking for everyone in the restaurant. I ordered the Lamb Patty Melt, Drip Coffee and Donut Balls. 

Drip coffee was the best coffee I've had for months. Maybe I do need to find something else other than Starbucks. 

Lamb Patty Melt was a little hard to grab so I ate them as a toast + the rest of the sandwich. It has the right amount of lamb flavor and the bread was awesome. So was the fried egg. 

Waiter was super friendly and he had two fried egg sewed at his shirt sleeves. Now I need to do some shopping to find sleeve patches that interesting.

text:
Aside from the staff being super friendly, the food is quite tasty and the environment is super chill yet a little hectic at the same time but it somehow works. 

What I appreciated the most about Milktooth, is you can really tell the food is made with good quality ingredients. I definitely had my heart set on the Sweet Tea Chicken Fried Biscuit and was a little bummed to hear they were sold out. However, the little bear plate was simple, yet delicious and paired nicely with a side of savory whey grits. Also, the slow drip coffee is on point .

Overall, Milktooth is a great addition to the Fletcher Place/Fountain Square area. I'm looking forward to spending many weekends at this place.

This is the second poor experience we've had here.  I don't normally write poor reviews but the hostess was so dismissive and rude on Mother's Day of all days and made no efforts to accommodate after having us wait for 90 min total.

text:
Always worth the wait. Filling this review out after I've gone a few times (5-6 times). Immaculate baked goods, inspiring latte combinations, creative soulful brunch food. I recommend grabbing a latte and a baked good to munch on while you wait. 

I've had few dishes I haven't loved.  I normally find it hard to narrow down the options, I normally ask the wait staff bc there always seems to be a few dishes that rise above the others. The sorghum bacon is always pretty impressive and a crowd pleaser and I've definitely ordered a few different versions of the Dutch baby. Happy brunching!

text: This place is amazing, and if you're a foodie you will be very impressed!  Do get there early though.  For the full menu, you need to be seated by 9, or you will have a wait.  We get there at 830 or 845 get pastries from the coffee bar and then order at 9... we have kiddo's so we don't like to wait too long.  By the way, it's great for kids, and the decor and vibe is very unique and awesome.  We love the lox pastry that you can get at the counter, their espresso is top notch, our kiddos love the ovaltine on the menu, and the boozy campfire cookies (although just a cookie, it is THE BEST cookie i've ever had) .  We've also had the cinnamon sugar donut holes (amazing!) and much more... but I'll just leave it at that.  Enjoy!

text: This is the kind of restaurant that can put Indianapolis on the map.  Exciting new flavor combinations, great vibe, excellent coffee.  The wait may be long but it gives you a chance to try out some of the pastries and fantastic coffees or drinks while you wait.  I love sitting at the bar and watching them cool the food, it helped me to decide to get the amazingly delicious grilled cheese.  Don't miss out on the bacon either!  Order it as a side and you can thank me later.  My wife got the sweet ditch baby and I got the savory and we shared.  I couldn't decide which was better.  Brave the crowd and just go already!

text:
This place is a delight for all the senses. Super cute and trendy, with tasty plates. A little on the pricier side, but they're always jam packed; they're worth it. I splurged for the "lox and cream cheese on a bagel" which they call "pastrami salmon with whipped cream cheese and fried capers". Fancy schmancy. Comes with micro greens on a wheat bagel. And it's delightful! Not an everyday food at $14, but a nice treat. 

Tea latte for $5, but again - a great treat and worth the occasional splurge.

I had a Stumbling Sailor and it was something I craved when I was on liberty in an over seas port and just woke up from a hard night out. Spicy, full of flavor and strong!

text:
The bustling hipster joint itself is very cool! The service was 100% on point! Even with all the tables being full there were seats at the bar so we didn't have to wait at all. The cooks are all out in the open so we watched them after we ordered our food. 

The only big complaint I have was the Bloody Mary. It was the one with the raw oyster in it. Oyster was delicious but the drink itself was God awful. Maybe bc I'm used to thicker tomato based bloody Mary's where this one was a carbonated, citrusy beverage. I wasted $10 bc I couldn't even tolerate choking it down. 

Better notes...the food:)
Glazed bacon... Very fatty buuuut thick cuts and the parts we could eat were amazing. 

Pistachio donuts served with a light crème and a few small orange slices were so delicious! They literally melted in your mouth. 

The liege waffle: my favorite item we ordered! Very light and fluffy. Served with whatever syrup was not too sweet and not drenched either. Served with 2 perfectly crunchy pieces of bacon and nuts sprinkled on top of the waffle. So good!

The Viking patti melt: perfectly cooked(a little pink inside) served with crispy French fries. The one and only complaint I had about this was the salt. They add salt onto the patti before they cook it... I would ask them to hold the salt if you decide to order this. I was on the verge of a stomach ache after eating 2 bites of this.

5 hours later... My stomach has been kind of messed up all day. Not sick but just unsettled. I'm on a plane right now so hoping nothing happens. My boyfriend just informed me that he's been stuck in the bathroom for the past 30 minutes. We had high hopes for this place:/

text: My heart has been stolen. I started with the mocha, which was pretty good, while waiting for a table. I was hoping to try the sweet tea fried chicken, but they had already run out. Bummer. There were three of us, so we asked for saucers so we could try each other's dishes. I tried the Uova al Forno. If I were a fast eater, I would've enjoyed it more. It was full of flavor, but there was bread under all of the sausage and spicy tomato sauce, so it got soggy quickly. The waffle was so, so good. Everything about it was right. It was a bit sweeter than I'm used to, but that was a welcomed change. The pork chop was really good, but I didn't have enough to share more about it. Sorghum glazed bacon was the winner. It's fatty on one side and meaty on the other. I'm pretty finicky when it comes to texture, but I was able to finish half of a piece. So. Good. It's salty, yet sweet... and amazing. Brady, our waiter, was friendly and knowledgable. The space is clean and there's plenty of natural light. Can't wait to go back and try the chicken everyone seems to love. Oh. The uncovered pastries up front... I would pass. I saw people reaching with bare hands, opening wallets over them, etc.
name: Milktooth

text:
What a unique addition to Indy! I had been wanting to stop by for awhile now but I am sort of a picky eater (I know...I wish I wasn't!) but I finally made my way there to give it a shot. Lucky enough, I found the Lamb patty melt on the menu that was calling to me. Amazing. Such a delicious sandwich with a side of quinoa grits with an egg, bacon and scallions. Coffee was good...I enjoyed the Crunch Berry Cappuccino. What a fun idea!

My one complaint is of course, the no exception rule to asking for an alteration on a dish. As a sometimes picky eater, that may steer me away from returning to try other items on the menu. And the food can be pricey. I left spending much more than I anticipated.

text:
The accolades for milk tooth keep rolling in as they continue to impress locally and nationally. I can't believe that it took indy this long to have such an amazing brunch place. Is it only a southern thing? I don't have much more to say that hasn't already been. But, chef Brooks and his whole team are doing brunch right and I hope indy treasures this local gem. I have long warranted this spot as a special occasion or celebratory meal but I think that the prices are incredibly accessible. I have never wanted to change anything to a dish I've had here so the complaints of that not being welcome don't ring true for me. 

Everything I have had here has been spectacular. The pastries and bakes goods are to die for. The coffee and concoctions from I believe the only mod bar in indy is superb. The sides are the highlights and the revolving menu never has disappointed. The staff and help are incredibly friendly. Especially the hostess. I salute you milk tooth you make indy a better place. 

(Tips)
Closed on Tuesdays!
Sorghum bacon, grits fully loaded, citrus glazed donut, all coffee, tea fried chicken)

text: I've been three times now, and can comfortably confirm that Milktooth is phenomenal. It is extremely likely that if you show up after 11 on a Friday or after 9 on a weekend you will encounter a wait. It's not a particularly pleasant wait as you will be jostled about by staff and other diners while gazing lustfully at the cooking station, or perhaps you will try to shove a pastry (oh, the pastries!) in your mouth while standing in hopes of abating your hanger, but it is a worthwhile wait. If you're vegan, you will perhaps feel constrained by the menu; the delicious porridge is your best bet. As far as innovative brunch fare goes, this place is the peak!

text: I heard of this place through a friend who is a chef. I was told the food was amazing, and the atmosphere was to die for. Unfortunately I didn't have the time of my life. As I look around, people are really enjoying themselves. The atmosphere is really friendly, but I also see a lot of food left on the plate. I ordered the Belgium waffle and the aroma of the salt on the waffle was very overwhelming. Long story short, the food was not up to par. I was very disappointed. The water wasn't cold, many items on the menu were sold out, and the ones they did have, they didn't allow any modifications to. The coffees were small and it was very hot inside. I really wanted to like this place. Unfortunately we didn't receive good service nor did we get a chance to even order what we wanted.

text:
I walked into Milktooth and the first thing I saw was a young man in a yellow cardigan and a feather earring freshly squeezing orange juice... and I knew I was in a magical place.  The atmosphere is super hipster, but there were all kinds of folks dining while we were there.  The restaurant is small but open and great for people watching.  The decor is delightful!- silverware is piled into an old coffee can and there are simple fresh flowers on each table.  

Oh yeah...the FOOD.  The menu is creative and unique.  I love this because I always feel like I could make other brunch places' offerings very easily at home. (Milktooth will take your run-of-the-mill hashbrowns and raise you a crispy potato latke topped with harrisa ketchup and aioli...)  I ordered the cornmeal pancake with fruit, cream, & cinnamon sugar- it satisfied my sweet tooth without being overly rich or heavy.  I paired it with the ricotta whey grits- they were perfectly (very simply) seasoned and very creamy.  Personally, I'm glad that Milktooth's portions aren't huge. I loved being able to select and try more than one menu item for my meal! Sweet + Savory = Success!  This morning I just had the bottomless drip coffee, which my server graciously filled 3 or 4 times.  Next time I'll try something fancier and maybe one of the pastries I was eyeing at the coffee bar.  Or the sorghum glazed bacon.  Or the lamb patty melt.  Or the uova al forno.  Time for more Milktooth!

text: The food is delicious.  Slightly on the pricey side, but totally worth the treat.  We lost our server for a little while, and at one point ended up asking someone else if they could let her know we were ready.  She came right away, and later the chef sent us some amazing fried donuts on the house.  Overall good service.  They were extremely busy, but all the staff looked cheery (and we had a perfect view of the kitchen from our bar stools).  I would definitely go back--since their menu changes all the time, every visit is a new adventure!

text: This place takes hipster to whole new level.  It's just too over the top in terms of breakfast offerings (they don't honor any food exceptions and they don't even offer a standard eggs and bacon option).  Everything is overly complicated, and takes about 3 looks to actually understand the menu.  I ordered the tofu salad, which was just blah.  My friend ordered the chocolate waffle - he said it was very chocolatey, but didn't have much else to say.  The service was slow and inattentive, even though the place was only a quarter full.  While I appreciate the great environment and decor, this place is just too over the top for me.

text: So let me start off by saying this is a 5 Star restaurant because the food scene in Indianapolis has nothing compared to this spot. Even though some of the food wasn't perfect in my opinion, it's incredibly innovative and unique! As a foodie, I loved getting a peach tart that tasted like it had ginger and thyme undertones. Or the savory grits with a perfectly cooked egg that was used to bring a velvety texture throughout the dish. Even though it's pricey and not everything on the menu will be your favorite, it is as special of a place as you will find in Indianapolis.

text:
Perfection all around - try everything on the menu. We had the Donut holes, bucatini carbonara with chili flakes, Dutch pancake with pumpkin spice, grilled raclette, as per servers recommendation.

Juice and coffee. The Bloody Marys looked big and popular. Inventive, creative flavors  you won't find everywhere. Highly recommended.  What a treat to have here in Indy! Thank you Milktooth.

text:
Every kind of hipster works here. Bearded leisure shirt, nautical sea captain, handlebar mustache, eggs on the elbows. 

This place is meant to savor. These people take their time to create a plate pleasing to both pallet and eyes. Talk, people watch, strike a convo with the person next to you. 

I went with the lamb patty melt and this fatty approves! I also had a chance to sample the ham and gruyere pancake and latke. So good! To drink, I had a latte, no sugar required, with foam treated like canvas.

I can't wait to revisit this place as the weather heats up and they begin to seat the patio and open those garage doors. 

5 stars across the sky!

text:
Went to Milktooth for the first time over the weekend while visiting Indianapolis. We sat at the bar and ordered brunch, and everything was outstanding! Even the guys behind the bar made great conversation with us! 

A word of caution, when they tell you the wings are hot, they aren't kidding! We also ordered a Cuban sandwich that was fantastic. We will definitely be back next time we are in the area!

Thanks for a great experience!

text:
You guys, I finally made it to Milktooth!  I have to say this place is amazing and I don't think my review will be any different than anyone else's.  So I'm just gonna get my complaints out of the way now so I can move on:
1.  You're almost too popular because I had to wait, outside in the rain, for an hour to be seated with my party.  (But I keep a commitment so I did it)
2. I don't like the disorganization of the coffee area or the prices of such. ($4 for a tiny cup? Come on, it's morning and mama needs some energy) also, I was practically shunned for asking for some cream and *gasp* sweetener for my iced coffee.  I'm a lady who knows what she wants and I really try to lay off the suga, so gimme my Splenda packet and we'll be ok.  

On to the good stuff.  Despite how busy they were, service was great.  I almost didn't feel cool enough to be there.  Everyone in their locally made apparel and handlebar mustaches, but I had on my best Hayes & Taylor shirt and crammed myself in anyways.  Of course I tried the bacon.  Do you consider that bacon?  It was half the size of a small pig, but none the less it was delicious!!  I had the pigs in a poncho to eat.  Soooo amazing!  That avocado cream sauce was just the perfect topping and the pickled veggies! I dream about being caught in a rainstorm wearing a poncho like that... 

I'll be back, and for my own selfishness I hope you are less busy :)

text: Our  server was awesome and that is the good news. My scrambled eggs & fried bacon was less than desirable. I think the fried bacon was made of salt pork it was so salty(to me anyway). If you are a foodie that loves eating whatever just to be different than you may love it. I prefer just plain good whether it be  unique or plain & simple. The other issue for me was the noise level inside. Music blaring and nothing to muffle sounds so don't count on a romantic chat. Go when it's warm to sit outside.

text: This place is so amazing. Don't let the long wait phase you one bit. There's an efficient coffee bar where you can have drinks (including a scrumptious Bloody Mary complete with a mini charcuterie stick) and pastries while you wait. I'm convinced that you could close your eyes and point at anything on the menu and be 100% satisfied. There is nowhere else in Indianapolis to even consider going for brunch if Milktooth is open. My advice is to come with an open mind and allow yourself to be extra indulgent!

text:
I love Milktooth  the food is absolutely amazing atmosphere is fun and  after my first visit I couldn't wait to go back.
I am very pleased that they serve their most beautiful and incredible coffee with a milk substitute. I love coffee and chocolate but after a certain age  I have had  to be very careful about the amount of caffeine my body can tolerate.  After my first visit I was up until 2 am but still couldn't wait to go back. Crazy about  this place!!!
Unfortunately after my visit at ~9 am this am I'm still awake. Even so, I am hopeful that someday decaf will be served. This is the only reason I only gave them 3 stars. It seems simple that I just wouldn't order coffee but I don't have that kind of will power

text: This place is easily one of the best in Indy!  Very unique menu that may not appeal to all as substitutions are "politely declined" per the menu, but there is no reason to request substitites! My wife ordered their grilled cheese and it was phenomenal! Cheese on the outside of the bread and inside topped with a sunny side up egg and the combination was exquisite! I ordered the tarte pancake, and it was to die for! Only open for breakfast and lunch, but definitely a must-stop at kind of place!

text:
After planning to meet friends for brunch in Indy, we decided on Milktooth. The restaurant is smaller and they have many community tables. We got there just at the right time for a Saturday, 10:30 am. Didn't have to wait for a table. The menu is unique, but for those brunchers who just enjoy simple eggs, toast, and bacon they'll make it. I ordered a Dutch baby with apples and the mocha. The coffee was a good, solid coffee. I was underwhelmed by the Dutch baby. It was good, but not great. Without the apples on top, the 'pancake' itself was very bland. I didn't taste any extra seasoning. I also felt that the $13 for the Dutch baby was a little high. Having made a Dutch baby myself and knowing the ingredients and how easy it is to make, I didn't feel like the $13 was warranted. 
Our service was good and the atmosphere was unique. The place gets very busy around 11, so be sure to plan ahead. It was a neat brunch place and would be a great place to visit when the weather gets nicer as they have outdoor seating. Parking is limited in the parking lot, but there was a lot of free parking on the street.

text:
So, I'm originally from the Bay Area, CA. Probably one of the most hipster spots in the country. Especially with Berkeley and Oakland just a hop and a skip away from where I grew up. Knowing that much about me, realize that Milktooth is quite literally the most hipster restaurant that I've ever been to in my life. From everything to the ghetto af music blasting for brunch, the mysteriously facial haired servers, and the quite random and ridiculous decor, everything just screamed hip and markedly cool. So, I was in my element. 

The food here is ridiculous. Their menu is filled with options that you'll read and then go, "wait wtf those ingredients didn't go together last I checked", but then you order it and it's so amazingly good and you're left questioning your own existence. Like their Manchengo and Grapfruit dutch baby? It's cheese and grapefruit baked into what's essentially a pancake. Just reading that, it's not supposed to taste good, but what the heck it's so yummy. I don't even get it. Every flavor bounces off each other so divinely that your tongue is left a little cooked after eating here. I'd honestly suggest just ordering together as a group and sharing everything that way you can try as many things as possible.

I personally loved the aesthetic of the restaurant though. It was very obviously a auto shop or a gas station or something of that sort previously; evidenced by the large garage doors adorning one side of the restaurant. Our server was very friendly and helpful when it came to the menu, so an A+ on that end. And the price was right around what I would have expected from a restaurant like this one. 

In all, it was one of the best meals I had on my trip to Indy. Definitely worth a visit.

text:
I loved this place.  Full disclosure, my husband thought that it was pretentious.  And it was, but not in a bad way.  He'd probably dock them a point for that, but I felt like it was just part of the ambiance.  It's not a diner, it's a fancy brunch place.  We had a 40 minute wait.  I don't know why restaurants in Indy don't text when the wait is up so we weren't able to go for a walk, but you could order coffee and pastry while you wait, which was pretty awesome.  Coffee is my friend.

I had the Nashville Hot Wings and they were great.  My waitress warned me about them, but I like hot so was in loooove.  The toddler "decided" to go with their potato/yuca latke (I think they called it a pancake) side for his meal and he really enjoyed it.  There was a kid's offering, but that sounded more interesting.  I had a neat cocktail, which always makes brunch better.

I love it and will be coming back.

text: I was in town from Chicago visiting a friend who is new to the city. We were looking for a place to have brunch and I instantly recognized Milktooth as I read about it in Food & Wine and couldn't forget the unique name. We walked in about 2:15 on a Wednesday and although they closed at 3, the staff were perfectly kind and accommodating and the restaurant had a few tables full. I instantly loved the kitschy decor and airy space. I got the cold brew and it was so refreshing. My friend and I split the grilled cheese, the burger and a grapefruit pastry. It was all so amazing but the grilled cheese was definitely the stand out for me. It was the perfect combination of salty and sweet and unlike anything I've ever tasted although the idea seems so simple. The burger was delicious as well but was missing a little something in the flavor the of patty. The pastry was absolutely perfect and it doesn't hurt that it's citrus season! I'd definitely go back the next time I'm in town to try the crispy cauliflower wedge and dutch baby to name a few. Living in Chicago, some of the best restaurants are just outside my door, but I have to say, I was seriously impressed with this place and the grilled cheese was among one of the best things I've put in my mouth!

text:
Food- 5/5 we had the sweet tea chicken over biscuits and gravy, it was gluttonly awesome.  The bacon lived up to the hype and the latkes were perfect. The pie crust pancakes were just ok for us.  I had a couple of the Radler beers which I haven't had since I lived in Germany, that was a very nice suprise.  My wife had a champagne vodka mix which she did not really care for but that is just a taste preference. 
Decor- 3/5 I don't think they particularly are going for any look, just a long lasting brunch place that will still be relevant in 10 years. 
Service- 5/5 our server had suggestions and opinions and really knew the menu.  We had to wait 40 mins with a baby and a 4 year old which was a pain in the ass but that is to be expected with a new hot spot.

It's a must visit Indy spot that has lasting power.

text:
Drove by after an early doctors visit. Hospitals make me hungry. Got the Pecan Bun and coffee. 
This sticky piece of heaven had me sold on the first bite. I'm talking fluffed pastry and sugary happiness filled my jaws. Coffee to dissolve the bun into itty bitty particles of joy. 
It lifted my day so much that even though I drove in the wrong direction home ; adding 20 min to my drive, I did not even care. 
Coffee had great aromatics and flavorful accents. Basically it tastes like love.

I didn't even mind the sticky remnants in my beard. They shall be missed.

text: I've been to Milktooth a few times and have had good luck with both meals. We went on a Sunday during prime brunch time and had to wait about 90 minutes. The coffee and cocktails (we got the coffee long island ice tea) are both very good (albeit very expensive). If the cocktails were just a few dollars cheaper we probably would have gotten more than one during our long wait. Once you are seated the service is very fast and friendly. They are very generous with their coffee refills.

text:
Interesting menu. I ordered the grilled chicken thighs with farro, gochugaru (sriracha-like) sauce, mint and cilantro. Balanced dish, good textures, and perfectly cooked protein.

We shared homemade biscuits with herb cream cheese, honey, and black pepper, and they were excellent.

Wife had grilled cheese with cranberry and walnut, raclette and Gouda cheese, and a black truffle honey. Good flavors, but lacking in texture. We couldn't identify the fruit or nuts, and I couldn't taste any truffle in the honey, though there were visible shavings. Was delicious, but not very well balanced, and felt very heavy. She at half and saved half for later.

I enjoyed a cocktail infused with CBD oil. Very tasty.

I like that there are no substitutions, no reservations, and no straws here. We came around 10:30 for brunch. We were seated around 11:15, and finished our meal around 12:15. Would return again.

text:
This is a cute little place with very delicious food. It's also very popular so waits can be long, but you can buy a coffee and sit with it in the outside waiting area which was pleasant. 

I deducted stars because this is one of the most pretentious places that I've ever eaten. I appreciate that the chef has a vision but no one really seemed to care if I actually enjoyed my meal. 

Other negatives: the centers of the doughnut holes were under cooked, they were out of pastries, the service was slow, the outside was pleasant but the inside was very loud with loud music (you're serving brunch, you aren't a bar!), and I left feeling hungry. 

I had the huevos rotos which were eggs scrambled with potatoes and dried meat with avocado purée. It had a nice flavor but  it was very small. We also had the grilled cheese, the Liege Belgian waffle, and the cinnamon and sugar donut holes. Our bill was $55 plus the $15 for three iced coffees.

text:
Not much of an out to eat breakfast guy so my words may fall flat. Having said that, I do make it out for the most important meal of the day occasionally. It was the first month of living in Indiana that my wife and I decided to pawn the child off to a family member so we could scout the town. March was still cold and the mid-week morning was gray and we Yelp'd great breakfast joints. And so we landed here by way of the reviews and didn't regret it!  My experience at Milktooth found me sunshine in the form of the BEST pour over coffee I could recall. So good that I had to ask Phil how he did it. Phil was very kind and even provided some coaching for my own novice barista ways.
I could go on and on about the fantastic pancakes and rave about the ancient grain porridge, but you just have to experience it yourself. I recall telling my wife, and our server, that this might have been the best breakfast experience in my life. But then again, how would I know, I don't get out that much for breakfast? I just know.
Well done Milktooth.

text:
Food was good. I had a decent breakfast but nothing to write home about. Other dish at the table had great flavor -the lamb burger but it was very small...maybe a 3oz patty cooked which isn't bad, in fact a welcome change to a gigantic burger, but it was 12 bucks. Come on....
Way too much hype around this place that should have told me to steer clear. I doubt I'll be back soon but perhaps when it comes back to earth. It was fun hanging out waiting for the table...quality people watching. Service was good and staff was very nice.

text: We came here based on the reviews.  But when we showed up on a late weekday morning we were a little scared.  It seemed a little to "hippie ish" for us.  It was raining and we were here so we gave it a try. Glad we did!  The love train coffee was AWESOME!  I had the Latke and she had the waffle.  We shared a side of bacon.  The bacon was so thick that it was like a piece of ham steak.  They were great and perfect sized.  Some places give you a ton of food and you waste half of it.  This was the perfect portion.  We were pleasantly surprised by this converted garage into a restaurant.  Keep up the good work and keep creating new things!

text: Thank you, Milktooth, for wasting my time on Mother's Day morning. This is the third time that I'm coming to you to have breakfast and it's the third time that I get disappointed - not by the food but by the service. I waited outside for two hours watching people who came after me being sat and I kindly and politely informed the hostess that I'm still there twice and was still ignored.  So, finally, as a big foodie, you lost a customer and those who dine with me.  I was really hoping to give you a five star review.

text: Gets really busy, so had to wait a while. However after being seated and getting our orders in, everything was great. Nice waitstaff. Latte was good, ribeye steak with egg was amazing, and the pancake with lemon curd and berries was great. At first it looked like a small portion, but I was thoroughly full by the end of it. text:
Thank the lord somewhere in Indianapolis can serve a decent espresso and a high quality breakfast in the same sitting! I just moved from Philadelphia and was a little worried 'little ole Indy' wouldn't have something to my snuff in the breakfast realm. 

The menu has an exquisite list of unique and/or local ingredients with each item having its own 'flare'. Even a side of bacon doesn't go unnoticed with its extremely thick cut and sorghum syrup. 

I took note of the coffee and appreciated the time and talent that went into each cup. They even serve a cortado.. A sure sign that someone behind the counter has some knowledge of coffee. The latte art I received was also beautiful, as a barista, that's important to me also. The micro foam was on point for my latte and for my husbands cortado. 

Not the place to take someone who just wants scrambled eggs and pancake. Come here to go to another level in the food world and to enjoy the presence of true passion, skill, and knowledge from the chefs and baristas. 

THANK YOU MILK TOOTH.

text:
Great first time experience here! I went here for Sunday brunch recently to see what all the hype was about. I definitely understand it. Food was delicious! 

Arrived around 12:30 to a very busy restaurant. Was told our wait would be about an hour. Luckily my boyfriend wasn't sure what to order so we spent most of the time getting suggestions and looking at pictures, while enjoying some coffee beverages. After an hour we were seated at the bar and placed our orders. I heard great things about the grilled cheese dish and my boyfriend settled with the Dutch pancake with apples. We ordered a side of bacon as well. 

Once the food came out, I dug in and enjoyed every bit of it. The touch of honey on the grilled cheese really brought the flavor together. I loved having the egg on top as well. The bacon - wow. We couldn't even finish all the bacon but I loved it. We both enjoyed our meals. The items on the menu may seem strange to a first timer, but trust that you will be satisfied with anything, so give it a shot. I would love to come back to try more. 

I gave it 4 out of 5 only because I need to try more before giving it the title of "best brunch in Indy", but I was definitely impressed with what I had!

text: I have been wanting to try this place for months after hearing so many good things about it. My wife and I finally got to eat here yesterday. I think my expectations may have been unrealistic, but we still ended up with a good dining experience. The wait staff was friendly and attentive. My wife got the Belgian waffle and a side of bacon. The waffle was perfectly textured and delicious. The "bacon" was closer to a 1/2" thick slice of pork belly (not that I am complaining). I got the famous sweet tea glazed chicken wings and a side of biscuits. The biscuit was the highlight of the meal for me. I may have never had a better biscuit in my life. The wings were part of an all-around well composed plate. Unfortunately I was less impressed with the coffee options. I really had high hopes for their coffee mocktails, but the two we tried were unexceptional. Also the $60 bill we ended up will make it difficult for us to eat here more than once in a blue moon. But my wife and I will probably come back when we feel like splurging, as the food was very good.

text: This place is great. Situated in a converted service garage, it is open for breakfast and brunch. The ambiance definitely gives off a cool vibe. All the way from the great staff to the herb garden in the front. I resisted the urge to call it the good funky.The food is a little different, but not in a bad way. I had the White Bloody Mary and the Uova Al Forno, $12, which is eggs baked in a spicy tomato sauce with amelia's semolina. Fantastic! Just the right amount of spicy. The bloody mary had a couple of unusual ingredients but was refreshing. My wife had the a mimosa with tangerine, which she was not fond of and the Little Bear Plate, $8, which is scrambled eggs, toast & jam with bacon and she liked it, except for the fact that there was just, what I would call a dab, of eggs. We think it is a little pricey, $48 with tax and tip, but that must be what they need. Our server, Brady, did a great job. We will return.

text:
Milktooth is one of the most talked about restaurants in all of Indianapolis, and with good reason. I went by myself one Saturday morning which significantly reduced my wait time. Larger parties will likely wait 30 minutes to an hour to be seated. I was seated at the bar by their grill area. This added to my experience as I was able to watch them prepare and plate all of the dishes. The menu is short but full of unfamiliar ingredients, so seeing the process up close demystified a few things.

I started my order with the most pleasantly designed mocha I've ever had. I'm not much of a coffee drinker, but I enjoyed the flavor and crafting. For breakfast I had the sorghum-glazed bacon and a sourdough zucchini bread waffle with peaches, orange cream cheese, and a cocoa drizzle. The bacon was so thick it's more resembles pork belly. The saltiness of the bacon went well with the sweetness of my waffle. Zucchini bread is great on it's own, but in waffle form it's even better. It was cooked just like I like, crispy outside and soft inside. All the elements really paired together well. On a future visit I'll be looking to try a lunch entree.

text:
This place is so popular and so loved I had high expectations. But I have to say that menu just wasn't doing it for me. There weren't that many options that seemed excited to me personally. Probably because they do a lot of turning a sweet dish into a savory one and that is opposite of what I'm interested in doing. 

I visited around noon on a Thursday and got the last spot in their small parking lot. I opted for sitting at the bar since I was there on my own. I looked over the menu and quickly decided to stick with a basic burger - always a go-to for me. I mentioned to the waitress that they could leave the bun off if they wanted. She informed me that, "the chef won't make it without a bun". Which was fine with me, I don't mind simply taking it apart myself. I just feel bad wasting food. 

I swear that only about three minutes passed before my burger was delivered! Talk about fast!! It is on the petite side, but is stacked two patties high and three pieces of bread sandwiching it together. This was a pretty solid burger - I found this particularly impressive considering the basic toppings!

text:
The pretentiousness of this place will practically knock you out the door but don't be alarmed, pull up your skinny jeans and wrap on that indoor scarf, Milktooth is worth a visit.
Busy, loud and the aforementioned, the food here is excellent.  Pricey for the serving size but worth it to your tastebuds.  Farm to table is cute for people not from rural areas so while the product is genuine the atmosphere is a bit smug, hipster (for sure) and overtly organic.
I can tell I'll have favorites here; the sorghum bacon, the waffle and the good coffee variety.  The antipasto plate is unbalanced though, over powered by the vegetable mix (too much pepperoncini?) the mild meat and cheese don't stand a chance.  Too much heat to enjoy the rest of the plate.
Service here seems a bit chaotic but they get the jog done, very informative and friendly staff, we enjoyed our visit all the more by the warm spirit showed to us.
I plan to go back but it's not going to be a regular spot, not enough value and while the staff was great the patrons are affected, which brings the overall experience down.

text: I had such high hopes for this place...really comfortable, nice place BUT the food...look I'm from Brooklyn, I get it you're the hipster joint in town.  The grits with egg, scallion & bacon were just ok.  The waffle yuck...dense like thick cardboard and as tough to chew, sickeningly sweet with the butter & honey & gross.  Super small portions of food that made my stomach upset that I then I got to pay $32 for the waffle I ate 1/2 of & the small portion of the grits/egg business along with coffee & OJ.  The food wasn't good & the prices are entirely too high.  It reeked of trying to hard to be hip & different with your wacky ingredients which would have been fine if the food actually tasted good & didn't upset my stomach.  You're not NY.  Won't be back.  I honestly would have rather gone to a diner for breakfast than spend the amount of money I spent on bad food that made me sick.

text:
I had a lot of expectations going into Milktooth based on the reviews I had been reading. I was excited because the concept of a restaurant with an upscale coffee bar was reminiscent of a restaurant (Cafe Medina) that I like to go to in my hometown of Vancouver. I also really liked that they serve several different beans from different roasters.

After eating at Milktooth, I must say that the food was just okay, and the iced coffee that I had was meh, while the regular drip was okay. I don't know if it was quite worth the 45 minute wait. I think my experience was dampened by the flies that kept flying into me, on my food, and drinking from my water glass. At one point, the waitress had come by to ask if everything was okay while a was holding my fork with a fly standing right on it.

I started with an iced vietnamese coffee. I was disappointed by it because it was very weak and watery. The floral flavor of the beans was there, it was the right type of beans and roast, but it was just too weak. I knew this was going to happen because when I was observing the coffee being made, the beans were not packed down enough to allow for the water to steep long enough and have a slower drip. Instead, the water was dripping down too fast into the glass, much like a typical pour over. This process resulted in a coffee whose color was more of an orange than an almost black brown, so when it was actually mixed with the condensed milk, it was almost a vanilla/peach color instead of medium coffee color. This may have been intentional on their part, to get drinks and orders through as quick as possible, but it was probably the worst iced vietnamese coffee I've ever had. It made it the worst because I was expecting my thick, full-bodied, acidic coffee with the richness of the condensed milk and the cooling effect of the ice.

For the food, we had the strawberry shortcake donut holes with whipped goat cheese. This was my favorite, it was definitely good. It made me more open to the idea of ordering more food after my main meal just because I wanted to try more stuff.  However, after I had my okonomiyaki (a favorite treat that I love to eat), and my partner had her Huevos, we did not want to order any more food. Not because we were full, but because we were underwhelmed and feeling like the food we got was overpriced for the quality.  My okonomiyaki was bland. It was missing something. The combination of egg, broken ramen noodles, and calamari really made it bland. I was expecting the bacon to add some flavor, and of course the okonomiyaki sauce and the japanese mayo, but because of the way the bacon was cooked, the full flavor of the bacon did not come through and added to the bland, somewhat fatty taste of the okonomiyaki. Perhaps the okonomiyaki would have benefitted from stronger green onions and some bonito.  As for the Huevos, I can't say much, except my partner commented that it would not have tasted like anything without the salmon, but something about the salmon was actually putting her off it. My partner really liked her mimosa though and said it's the best she's had in a while.

So overall? My experience was okay, a bit underwhelming and based on the food that I received, I thought it was a bit overpriced. Will I come back? I will probably come back for the drinks, and maybe try the tea wings and other pastries.

text: Love this 'fine diner'!  Very creative dishes, fresh, locally sourced ingredients, friendly, genuine staff, great re-purposed furnishings and decor, great vibes and energy!  What's not to like?!  This is NOT your mom's diner or breakfast or brunch!  Their bacon with sorghum glaze is wonderful!  The drip coffee is bottomless and beans come from local Bee Roasters.  Located in a former garage, this innovative new Indy dining spot will definitely fix whatever ails ya!  Only 58 seats inside so come early or settle back with a warm, aromatic coffee and people and food watch!

text: I was underwhelmed overall by Milktooth. I met some business colleagues there for breakfast at 8:00 on a weekday. They opened at 7:00. Our waitress informed us that full breakfast would not be available until 9:00. The music was insanely loud until about 8:30, when they turned it down. We were the only 3 people there for a while, so perhaps the music was up loud for the employees to enjoy? We could barely hear each other talk, and it was way too early for that loud of music for me. The coffee, however, was phenomenal. It was definitely the best, most fresh, and most balanced coffee I have ever had from anywhere. I made plans to stop by on my way to Lilly to grab a coffee some morning. The pastries were very unique. I am not too adventurous when it comes to food, so I'm probably not the best judge of the overall menu, but I really liked the tres leche pastry - bread pudding and beer. Very sweet and lightly tangy. From glancing at the breakfast menu, it was a little weird for my tastes, but again, I am conservative when it comes to food. I will definitely try to swing by and grab a coffee to go sometime, but I don't plan to try and eat in here anytime soon.

text:
What an awesome experience. We arrived at around 9 on Presidents' Day and were seated in about 10 minutes. As we waited we got the bottomless drip, which was very tasty. They offer honey and other regular mix-ins for  your coffee, but I prefer mine black. We also got a sticky pecan bun. I highly recommend this to anyone. It is so doughy and sweet!!!! 

As we were seated, we were immediately waited to and served water and more coffee. I don't understand the bad reviews for service here. Our service was fantastic and all of the workers were so nice and informative. 

The food: we got the Apple Dutch baby pancake, blue corn grits, sorghum glazed bacon, and carrot cake waffle. All of the food was exceptional. I read the reviews on the grits, and being that I'm not a huge fan of grits, I was skeptical, but man were these grits good! The pancake was delicious also. I loved the crunch given by the celery and crisp apples on top; however, I do wish it was a bit more sweet. The bacon was probably the best part of our meal, besides the sticky bun:). I wasn't a huge fan of the carrot cake waffle, and I would recommend getting something else, as there are much better items on the menu. It wasn't horrible by any means, it just wasn't the best.

I love Milktooth, and I'm now gonna be one of those many people that hype it up. Keep up the good work and creative thinking! I will definitely be back to try that grilled cheese with the egg on top, and I want to see what this barista has really got.

text:
A cool hipster place! This is the place for a funky fun brunch. We enjoyed brunch on a busy Saturday morning. The walk up wait was about 15 minutes so we grabbed a drink at the indoor cafe and sat outside on their waiting area. 

Not a large menu so take a look to make sure you like something on the menu or if you're adventurous they do have some fun combinations.

Their waffle and grilled cheese were pretty awesome. Our meals were good size, but most of their stuff is tapas.

text: The ambiance is good in itself but the food is mediocre for the price that you're paying. I feel like the dish that I got was a bit too much for what it was. I really didn't understand why there was so much mustard in a dish with lentils and sausage. Every bite that I took was basically mustard filled. The sausage was good though. But you honestly don't get that much food for what you pay. If you come here, is more for the look of the place than anything. And I also don't recommend if you want breakfast food. It's more lunch than breakfast.

text: Upon entering this location, you feel as if you have been moved to an area in San Francisco. A wonderful new environment that provided a plethora of bloody marys.  The food was excellent. Chicken and waffles were well done. Balanced flavors. Chicken pieces were well fried and the protein was not over cooked. However, this was a very small portion and I would say it could certainly have been a larger portion for brunch.

text:
The stuff you have heard about Milktooth is true. They have an eclectic brunch menu that rotates with some pretty special dishes. If you are looking for your traditional eggs benedict, go somewhere else. If you are looking to try something original with a lot of flavor, this is your place. It just depends on your mood. I have had the best restaurant waffle here, some incredible pastries, and some particularly creative brunch dishes. 

Most of the time there is a long wait, but most of the time it is well worth it. This is a place you should try at least twice. This is a special place.

text: What a fun place to go for brunch! The atmosphere is great but be prepare to wait for a table if you're in a group. We sat at a counter so we could be seated sooner. Service was a little slow but they made up for it with the food! I should also mention they were very busy. Sitting along the counter we were able to watch as food was prepared and boy did it look good! I tried the Welsh Rarebit Dutch Baby Pancake! It was pretty tasty but I plan to try one of their sweet entrees next time. The rest of my crew tried the Grilled Cheese and it was out of the park! Served hot and melts with an egg on top! If the service had been just a tad quicker, I'd give it 5 stars. If drinks are in your future, you definitely want to try their Bloody Mary!

text:
A long overdue review, but I definitely wanted to document my memory of my first time here. Milktooth is like having a culinarily gifted best friend with retro bohemian style that welcomes you to the day with sunshine & mimosas. I could literally have a back bedroom in this space & love my life.

And the food...

I had no idea what to expect; I had only heard the place was good. To be honest, I read through the menu & my first impression was that the place was unnecessarily pretentious. Because I arrived a little later than the breakfast hours, the menu options were not the brunch offerings I had envisioned. I ended up ordering the rye bialy with big eye tuna salad...I really bad no idea what was about to arrive... I mean, what the heck is bialy?

Turns out, bialy is a bagel type bread...who knew? Atop the bialy was the tuna salad, a whipped cream cheese, red onions, salad greens and lots of capers. Final verdict: pretentious...perhaps...delicious...most definitely. This place can be as pretentious as it wants because they have created such an inviting space to serve creative,  delicious food. Bravo!

text:
Overall, between the ambience  food quality and overall experience, Milktooth is absolutely a place I would go again.  In fact although I search on yelp often I have only written two reviews in the past year with Milktooth being one of those two places.  Now prior to reading this review, I'd like to remind you that I lived in New York City as well as Miami so I have tried a lot of different types of restaurants.  

           Even though on a Sunday afternoon the wait was well over an hour it was worth it.  However during that hour wait you're still able to order coffee drinks as well as pastries and enjoy those while awaiting your table.  The backdrop setting for the place is reminiscent of a automobile repair garage shop.  

         As far as the food is concerned we ordered a grilled cheese sandwich which came out with a egg on top as well as syrup.  The honey syrup on top was a perfect blend of sweet and savory.  The bread was cranberry walnuts with a local cheese. The person I was with is not a fan of calamari, but she was willing to give the shrimp and calamari brussel sprout dish a shot and afterwards she said that she would order it again.   

            Overall I had a great experience there and I think anybody within the area absolutely needs to try this restaurant.  I only wish is it was closer to my house, but then I think my pants would eventually not fit me.  As I am proofreading this and revisiting my meal I kind of wish it was open right now :D

           My biggest complaint is that this restaurant is not open for a dinner menu because I think they would do an amazing job.

text: This place is great for trying something a little different but not too far off the beaten path.  You'll probably want to order multiple things off the menu! The wait can long and no reservations but it's worth it.  It's a very welcoming atmosphere and even though it's always busy the service never feels rushed.  Spend a lunch or brunch here with friends and you'll leave planning your return.

text:
From my first visit to the last Milktooth has that somethin' somethin' that keeps me coming back for more. I think it's the sexy sorghum glazed bacon, yes, most definitely the bacon and probably the Sweet Tea Fried Chicken and the Dutch Baby Cornmeal Pancake but most definitely the bacon. 

Here's the nitty-gritty:

Space/Ambiance - Open, inviting, and captivating. From the coffee bar to the open concept kitchen "to the windows to the walls" there is something magically creative happening here and it's exciting just to sit back and watch. 

Drinks - A wide and vast assortment ranging from artfully presented espresso drinks and pour overs, to cocktails, beer, and wine. I might be so bold to say their latte is one of the best I have had in a long time. The presentation and the addition of Traders Point Creamery milk adds a special local touch. The bottomless house brewed coffee on the other hand was a bit strong for my liking, but wasn't undrinkable, just a bit too rich for me. I have not yet had the pleasure to enjoy one of their cocktails. I do have my eye on the White Bloody Mary. Next time! 

Food - I have tried the Sweet Tea Fried Chicken, Belgian Waffle, Dutch Baby Pancake (sweet variation), Uova AL Forno w/grilled Merguez Sausage, Sorghum Glazed Bacon, and the Chocolate Shortbread. The Sweet Tea Fried Chicken is a great dish and is consistently delicious. The gravy and chicken pair so well together like a perfect harmony. If you order the Uova Al Forno add the Sausage. It definitely adds to the dish bringing in great flavors. I really enjoyed the Dutch Baby Pancake & Belgian Waffle but felt the portion size was small without the addition of a accompaniment from the adjacent menu. This can be good or bad depending on how you look at it. Good if you want to pair a few dishes together but bad if your on a budget.

My Experience - Most recently I decided to share Milktooth with family which included my dad who is the pickiest eater on earth. He simply refuses to eat anything green and sneers at ingredients like pickled avocado and clementine confit. Knowing full well "modifications are politely declined" I was a little uneasy and had my fingers crossed that he too would have a pleasant experience. To my amazement the man who hates most food groups loved his Belgian Waffle! Hallelujah there is hope!

Special Notes - I like that you can enjoy a coffee and/or pastry while waiting for your table. It's also nice to be able to get these freshly made items to-go if your short on time. 

PS: Just writing a review about Milktooth is making me hungry to go back. Word on the street is the Cinnamon Sugar Potato Doughnuts are mind blowing!

text:
Words cannot express how amazing this place is. I almost don't even know why I'm writing a review because what else can possibly be said?! If you live in the state of Indiana and you have not been to Milktooth - GET WITH THE PROGRAM. What's holding you back? The countless amazing reviews? The countless awards? Milktooth literally made it onto a reputable list of top new restaurants IN THE WORLD. Google it. 

So, I had the grilled cheese. Sounds simple and boring, right? Nope. If it were legal, I would seriously consider marrying this thing. It is, hands down, in my top 5 favorite meals EVER. And I love food. I've had lots and lots of food. It's just THAT good. Salty and sweet is my absolute favorite combination, and this meal nails that directly on the head. It's fabulous beyond words. 

The bacon. What to say about the bacon? ALSO AMAZING! It's so thick, and it's covered in this sweet sorghum glaze, and it's the perrrrrrfect consistency/texture, and I just love it. It's basically a huge chunk of salty/sweet meat. Get in my belly. 

The coffee is also superb. Lots of breakfast places serve-up burned coffee simply because it has been sitting in a pot all day. Not cool. 

I can't say that I'm a huuuuge fan of the layout, though. I despise communal eating, and some tables are definitely meant to accommodate multiple parties. This isn't NYC. I'd like to disgustingly devour my bacon meat chunk in solidarity and peace. 

Tip 1) Know that Milktooth is not cheap. My meal (without the bacon and coffee included) was $16, at the time. Whoa! But it's worth it. 

Tip 2) Expect a wait. Even with only 2 people in my party, I've never gotten in without at least a 30 minute wait. But again, it's worth it. 

Tip 3) Order a pastry and some coffee while you wait! Just head on inside to the counter, and order up. 

With all of that being said, I heart Milktooth.

text: I was so excited to go to Milktooth because whenever someone found out I was moving to Indy, it was the one restaurant that everyone agreed I needed to try. I went with my parents on a Sunday morning and we attempted to have brunch. However, our waitress was not accommodating or pleasant. I ordered a chocolate croissant and she brought me the pistachio key lime croissant, which I didn't realized until my first bite. She then insisted it was the correct  croissant. My mom has some food allergies and asked if she could hold one of the ingredients  on an entree, but the waitress said they do not remove ingredients because it takes away from the intended taste of the dish. To say the least, she was very unaccommodating and downright rude. When our food finally came out, it was "okay" nothing too live for. It's unfortunate that this raved about restaurant was so tainted by such an unpleasant waitress. It's hard to differentiate between the poor service and mediocre food. I'm willing to try this restaurant again, but my hopes aren't high for it living up to its name.
